revision.text:
'''Basamum''' was a deity worshipped in pre-[[Islam]]ic South [[Arabia]]. His name may be derived from the proto-[[Arabic language|Arabic]] ''basam'', or [[Balsam of Mecca|balsam]], a plant that was used in ancient medicines, indicating that he may have been a deity associated with healing or health.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=aqDC5bwx4_wC&pg=PA47&dq=Basamum+deity&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjA4qTny_TSAhWqC8AKHRX0C7kQ6AEIMTAE#v=onepage&q=Basamum%20deity&f=false|title=Dictionary of Gods and Goddesses|last=Jordan|first=Michael|date=2014-05-14|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=9781438109855|language=en}}</ref> One ancient text referred to Basamum curing two sick [[Goat|goats]] or [[Ibex|ibexes]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=0La5CAAAQBAJ&pg=PT66&dq=Basamum+deity&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj3tdWwy_TSAhXhI8AKHQ0dAw0Q6AEIHDAA#v=onepage&q=Basamum%20deity&f=false|title=A Dictionary of Gods and Goddesses, Devils and Demons|last=Lurker|first=Manfred|date=2015-04-29|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781136106200|language=en}}</ref> 

