'''[[Cannabis]] in [[Yemen]]''' is illegal, and is less common than [[khat]].<ref name="Crime2004">{{cite book|author=United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime|title=World Drug Report 2004|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FWbHFitRELsC&pg=PA1996|year=2004|publisher=United Nations Publications|isbn=978-92-1-148185-3|pages=1996–}}</ref>

==History==
Cannabis is listed as one of the agricultural products of Yemen during the [[Rasulid dynasty]] (1229-1454).<ref name="Mackintosh-Smith2014">{{cite book|author=Tim Mackintosh-Smith|title=Yemen: The Unknown Arabia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m2QjCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT151|date=3 June 2014|publisher=The Overlook Press|isbn=978-1-4683-0998-0|pages=151–}}</ref>

==Economy==
Yemen is Saudi Arabia's principal source of drugs.<ref name="Mart’nez2011">{{cite book|author=ê–igo MorŽ Mart’nez|title=The Borders of Inequality: Where Wealth and Poverty Collide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QazKoWJprysC&pg=PA52|date=15 May 2011|publisher=University of Arizona Press|isbn=978-0-8165-2932-2|pages=52–}}</ref>

In 2007, Yemen was the fifteenth-most prolific producer of [[cannabis resin]], comprising 0.4% of seized cannabis globally.<ref name="Hill2017">{{cite book|author=Ginny Hill|title=Yemen Endures: Civil War, Saudi Adventurism and the Future of Arabia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-k0rDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA317|year=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-084236-9|pages=317–}}</ref>

