{{Orphan|date=March 2018}}
'''Golfer's vasculitis''', '''exercise-induced vasculitis''' and '''hiker's rash''', are names proposed by different medical researchers for a form of [[vasculitis]] resulting in a purpuric [[rash]] (bleeding from underlying [[Tissue (biology)|tissues]]).<ref name="pmid15670170">{{cite journal|last=Kelly|first=RI|author2=Opie, J |author3=Nixon, R |title=Golfer's vasculitis.|journal=The Australasian Journal of Dermatology|date=Feb 2005|volume=46|issue=1|pages=11–4|doi=10.1111/j.1440-0960.2005.00127.x|pmid=15670170}}</ref> It is often experienced in the lower legs caused by excessive exercise in hotter temperatures. It is more common among older people.
It is called 'Golfer's' due to the large amount of walking done in [[golf]], as well as it being a sport more popular among older people, resulting in greater incidence of the condition.
