'''Program Resources and Outcomes Management Information System''' (PROMIS) is the first [[World Wide Web|web-based]] [[Case management (USA health system)|case management]] system for [[Head Start Program|Head Start]] and other [[Social work|social service]] organizations. It has been developed by Cleverex Systems, Inc.<ref>[http://promisinfo.cleverex.com/ Program Resources and Outcomes Management Information System] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425054237/http://promisinfo.cleverex.com/ |date=2012-04-25 }}</ref>

==The project==
PROMIS is built upon the Kynamic just in time knowledge technology.  This solution platform covers the complete service cycle and outcome analysis including:

* Client intake
* Screening and assessment
* Goals establishment
* Service plan
* Service delivery
* Outcome tracking
* Analysis and evaluation

Automation for real-time case tracking eliminates gaps in the service delivery process and reduces redundancy and fragmentation of services. PROMIS provides support for all client-service functions of an agency from "outreach to outcome." Through the use of [[Internet protocol suite|Internet technologies]] and a development approach built on [[business process re-engineering]] and extensive user involvement, the PROMIS system improves client service by reducing paperwork, automating [[Policies and Procedures|policies and procedures]] and integrating the delivery system within Head Start agencies.

The PROMIS project effort was funded by the Offices of Head Start, ACF from 2001 through 2003. Although the first [[Development stage|beta version]] became available for Head Start agencies to use free of charge back in 1999, the first production release was not available until the summer of 2004. Since its first release, PROMIS' user base has been increasing by about 100 new organizations a year. <!--This fast growth has been attributed by several factors:

* Relatively low cost;
* The user community has been actively involved (thousands of people participated);
* Commercially mature;
* Scalable.--Not supported by source material-->

A large majority of the so-called mega agencies (serving 10,000 families or more) have been using the PROMIS system for their daily operation.

